<div id="review_158572942" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/158572942" />
    <a title="Andreea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1245700-andreea"><img alt="Andreea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1243150661p2/1245700.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/158572942?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andreea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andreea" href="/user/show/1245700-andreea">Andreea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143105299" href="/book/show/1783073.The_Book_of_Sand_Shakespeare_s_Memory">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer158572942" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7685969014775815069">I fail to see what could have made so many people feel disappointed by this book. Perhaps it&apos;s just the fact that unlike most English speaking Borges readers, I was already well accustomed with Borges&apos; less fantastical and erudite stories and poems instead of viewing him solely through the prism of <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17717.Labyrinths' title='Labyrinths by Jorge Luis Borges' rel='nofollow noopener'>Labyrinths</a>. I found the whole book wonderful and painfully sad at the same time. I think my feelings towards it would be best explained by a quote from the book itself: <i>I felt what we always feel when</i></span>
  <span id="freeText7685969014775815069" style="display:none">I fail to see what could have made so many people feel disappointed by this book. Perhaps it's just the fact that unlike most English speaking Borges readers, I was already well accustomed with Borges' less fantastical and erudite stories and poems instead of viewing him solely through the prism of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17717.Labyrinths" title="Labyrinths by Jorge Luis Borges" rel="nofollow noopener">Labyrinths</a>. I found the whole book wonderful and painfully sad at the same time. I think my feelings towards it would be best explained by a quote from the book itself: <i>I felt what we always feel when someone dies - the sad awareness, now futile, of how little it would have cost us to have been more loving.</i> I dunno about you, but I did feel like something died after I finished the book. I love reading the complete works of writers - even writers whose writing I don't like that much. I love knowing that I'm one of the very few people who had the patience and dedication necessary to examine the soul of another human being so carefully and thoroughly. But as Borges reminds us somewhere else, we can never read all books and there's no use in trying. I own a complete works edition of his works, but I can't but feel melancholy reading the last volume he ever published and wonder how much of it I will get to read before I die. And even if I manage to complete it (which, given my very poor Spanish, I doubt) how many times I'll have the opportunity to reread and how many other stories and poems ideas he didn't get to put in practice he had before he died. Last books are as sad as unfinished manuscripts - at least you can reproach manuscripts they're untidiness, their spelling mistakes and plot holes, Borges is exquisite as ever in this book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7685969014775815069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


