<div id="review_2050744902" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2050744902" />
    <a title="তানজীম Rahman)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35042455-rahman"><img alt="তানজীম Rahman)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478579683p2/35042455.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2050744902?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="তানজীম Rahman)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="তানজীম Rahman)" href="/user/show/35042455-rahman">তানজীম Rahman)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2050744902" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11506144884388889079">Borges is like Kafka for people who aren&apos;t morbidly depressed.<br/>They both looked at the modern age through the lens of mythology and dreams. They managed to describe truths about the condition of the modern man, using not merely drab realism, but imagery previously reserved for epics and legends. <br/>But that&apos;s where the similarities between these two great authors end, at least in my opinion.<br/>Kafka looked at the modern world and saw monsters. Monsters whose tentacles take the forms of family, career, </span>
  <span id="freeText11506144884388889079" style="display:none">Borges is like Kafka for people who aren't morbidly depressed.<br />They both looked at the modern age through the lens of mythology and dreams. They managed to describe truths about the condition of the modern man, using not merely drab realism, but imagery previously reserved for epics and legends. <br />But that's where the similarities between these two great authors end, at least in my opinion.<br />Kafka looked at the modern world and saw monsters. Monsters whose tentacles take the forms of family, career, the judicial system and society itself.<br />Borges looked at the same world with a sense of wonder. To him, the universe was a labyrinth. The joy lies not in finding a way out of the labyrinth, but discovering new twists and turns along the path. <br />He was particularly interested in how the macrocosm is reflected in the microcosm. How the beauty and glory of the sun can be found in the humble sunflower. Perhaps the advent of quantum mechanics during his lifetime, that science which hints at the hidden complexities of our own universe, had a part to play in his vision of the world.<br />He was also, obviously, one of the most educated people of his time. His writing is rich with references to both ancient and modern literary classics. Classics both real and imaginary. His love for the medium spills over from the page and splashes the reader. I would love to one day establish a library filled only with books referenced by Jorge Luis Borges.<br />This book, in particular, is not among his most loved. But I enjoyed it thoroughly. I found it clear, precise, written by a man who has made peace with the purpose he has chosen in life. Some stories here are better than others, as is the case with every collection of short fiction. But overall the book has an excellent, uplifting effect on the soul.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11506144884388889079" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


