<div id="review_314963631" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/314963631" />
    <a title="Lucas Leite" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6712675-lucas-leite"><img alt="Lucas Leite" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608409984p2/6712675.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/314963631?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lucas Leite" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lucas Leite" href="/user/show/6712675-lucas-leite">Lucas Leite</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9788579490477" href="/book/show/13599001-o-livro-de-areia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer314963631" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1039616441645653758">More impressions <a href='http://www.criticaartesanal.blogspot.com' rel='nofollow noopener'> in my personal blog of reviews</a><br/><br/><b>It wasn&apos;t iPad, neither internet, it was sand (or paper)</b><br/><br/>&quot;The number of pages in this book is no more or less than infinite.<br/> None is the first page, none the last&quot;<br/>Jorge Luis Borges - The Sand Book<br/><br/>Reference to one of the tales, The Book of Sand is a small compendium of 13 short stories of the Argentine writer Jorge Luis Borges. Together, these stories have in common the fantastic nature of the peculiar writing of Borges. But more than that, the 13 st</span>
  <span id="freeText1039616441645653758" style="display:none">More impressions <a href="http://www.criticaartesanal.blogspot.com" rel="nofollow noopener"> in my personal blog of reviews</a><br /><br /><b>It wasn't iPad, neither internet, it was sand (or paper)</b><br /><br />"The number of pages in this book is no more or less than infinite.<br /> None is the first page, none the last"<br />Jorge Luis Borges - The Sand Book<br /><br />Reference to one of the tales, The Book of Sand is a small compendium of 13 short stories of the Argentine writer Jorge Luis Borges. Together, these stories have in common the fantastic nature of the peculiar writing of Borges. But more than that, the 13 stories have characterized the detachment boundaries imposed by matter, space and time, they become infinite in meanings, oneiric, malleable as the sandy ground - "... was named Book of Sand, because neither the book nor the sand have beginning or end".<br /><br />The Book of Sand whether dealing with a universe of double existence (The Other), of love (Ulrikke), of unknown (There Are More Things), of memories (The Night Of The Gifts), of secret society of holistic intentions (The Congress), of heresy (The Sect of Thirty), of fantasy based on the word (The Library of Babel; Undr, The Mirror And The Mask), of a gloomy future (A Weary Man's Utopia), of ethics (The Bribe), of political assassination (Avelino Arredondo), adverse or inconceivable object (The Disk; The Book of Sand), has in its lines a touch of Salvador Dali's surrealism. <br /><br />Like the book presented in Borges' short story, The Book of Sand has in its few pages a polysemic and polisemic composition, guaranteeing a unique experience of reading and meanings to each query. Here is the amazing merit of Borges: making the unbelievable property of an infinite book in the fable, became reality through the reduced possibilities and dimensions of the paper.<br /><br /><br />***<br /><br /><b>Não era iPad, tampouco internet, era areia (ou papel)</b><br /><br />“O número de páginas deste livro é infinito. <br />Nenhuma é a primeira,nenhuma, a última” <br />Jorge Luis Borges - O Livro de Areia<br /><br />Referência a um dos contos, O Livro de Areia trata-se de um pequeno compêndio de 13 contos do escritor argentino Jorge Luis Borges. Reunidos, estes contos têm em comum a natureza fantástica da peculiar escrita de Borges. Não obstante, mais do que isso, os 13 contos possuem como característica o desapego às delimitações impostas pela matéria, o espaço e o tempo, fazem-se infinitos na acepção, oníricos, maleáveis como o terreno arenoso - "... se chamava Livro de Areia, porque nem o livro nem a areia têm princípio ou fim".<br /><br />O Livro de Areia quer tratando de um universo de dupla existência (O Outro), do amor (Ulrica), do desconhecido (There Are More Things), das memórias (A Noite Dos Dons), de uma sociedade secreta de intenções holísticas (O Congresso), da heresia (A Seita dos Trinta), da fantasia baseada na palavra (A Biblioteca de Babel; Undr; O Espelho e a Máscara), de um melancólico futuro (Utopia de Um Homem Cansado), da ética (O Suborno), de um assassinato político (Avelino Arredondo), de objetos adversos ou inconcebíveis (O Disco; O Livro de Areia), possui nas suas linhas um quê do surrealismo presente em Salvador Dali.<br /><br />Tal qual o livro do conto título, O Livro de Areia possui em suas poucas páginas uma composição ao mesmo tempo vertiginosa e polissêmica, garantindo uma experiência única de leitura e com diferentes significados a cada consulta. Eis o espantoso mérito de Borges: tornar a inacreditável propriedade de um livro infinito presente na fábula, em realidade através das reduzidas possibilidades e dimensões do papel.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1039616441645653758" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


