<div id="review_4080798057" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4080798057" />
    <a title="Pictures at an Exhibition" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10375967-pictures-at-an-exhibition"><img alt="Pictures at an Exhibition" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616361334p2/10375967.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4080798057?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pictures at an Exhibition" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pictures at an Exhibition" href="/user/show/10375967-pictures-at-an-exhibition">Pictures at an Exhibition</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788845932885" href="/book/show/41125853-il-libro-di-sabbia">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4080798057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7287769067204601570">Borges is one of those few authors who has kept me company since the beginning of my life as a reader. His erudite inventive scenarios and his microcosmos of logical paradoxes have been the fuel of my escapism for as long as I can remember. On my journey to possess and read everything that was penned by him, including his <i>bestiarios</i> and dream journals, I stumbled upon this late collection of short stories . It is probably a minor work, even if <i>The Congress</i> and <i>The Book of Sand</i> are close to the p</span>
  <span id="freeText7287769067204601570" style="display:none">Borges is one of those few authors who has kept me company since the beginning of my life as a reader. His erudite inventive scenarios and his microcosmos of logical paradoxes have been the fuel of my escapism for as long as I can remember. On my journey to possess and read everything that was penned by him, including his <i>bestiarios</i> and dream journals, I stumbled upon this late collection of short stories . It is probably a minor work, even if <i>The Congress</i> and <i>The Book of Sand</i> are close to the peaks of the most famous Borgesian <i>ficciones</i>. It goes without saying, they are still a wondrous experience. But maybe you should not trust an overt fangirl. <br /><br /><i> There is nothing but quotations left for us. Our language is a system of quotations. </i></span>
  <a data-text-id="7287769067204601570" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
