    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_963740857" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/963740857" />
    <a title="Magdalena" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7356331-magdalena"><img alt="Magdalena" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1454602635p2/7356331.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/963740857?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Magdalena" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Magdalena" href="/user/show/7356331-magdalena">Magdalena</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7356331-magdalena?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer963740857" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6064998716125346054">Fascinating. Now I understand why people practically worship Borges. This book is the literary equivalent of a hot cup of real tea. Not a herbal infusion, but real, distilled camellia sinensis leaves. It is a smooth read, sometimes bitter and sometimes relaxing. <br/><br/>The stories in The Book of Sand are important for the way they deal with their respective themes. Most of the stories aren&apos;t particularly exciting on their own, one must relish their true meaning. It is a hedonistic read, but it also has</span>
  <span id="freeText6064998716125346054" style="display:none">Fascinating. Now I understand why people practically worship Borges. This book is the literary equivalent of a hot cup of real tea. Not a herbal infusion, but real, distilled camellia sinensis leaves. It is a smooth read, sometimes bitter and sometimes relaxing. <br /><br />The stories in The Book of Sand are important for the way they deal with their respective themes. Most of the stories aren't particularly exciting on their own, one must relish their true meaning. It is a hedonistic read, but it also has a purpose. The themes vary and touch on first love, reality, the importance of memory in knowledge and its reliability, vanity and ethics, the sublimity of language and words, and if that isn't enough, they feature a book of infinite pages, a real life hyperbole, a story in memory of H.P. Lovecraft, a time travelling Doppelgaenger... You'll have to read it yourself to wonder at the mysteries Borges brings to life in realistic, magical fiction. In such few words, Borges creates each atmosphere flawlessly, so one may think to have personally attended The Congress, the king's halls in The Mirror and the Mask, and accompanied Avellino Arredondo during his self-imposed exile. <br /><br />One of my favorite stories was the tribute to Lovecraft, There Are More Things. The title alludes to Hamlet ("There are more things in heaven and earth, Horatio, Than are dreamt of in your philosophy") Pure Lovecraftian terror, Borges style.<br /><br />Another favorite was Utopia of a Tired Man, which demonstrates a future where humans have maximized their capacities, and are mostly tired, waiting for Death. The conversation is touched by nostalgia and melancholy. <br /><br />The one I didn't like was Ulrikke, just because as a woman I know Ulrikke was created solely for the purpose of being a hyper-romanticized, fleeting love subject. Perhaps Borges felt this way about women, but I find it tedious and unreal.<br /><br />I will reread this again, just to find out more things to discover in each story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6064998716125346054" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


