<div id="review_831333290" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/831333290" />
    <a title="Rose" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4280522-rose"><img alt="Rose" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1453749585p2/4280522.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/831333290?book_show_action=true">Jan 22, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rose" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rose" href="/user/show/4280522-rose">Rose</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143105299" href="/book/show/1783073.The_Book_of_Sand_Shakespeare_s_Memory">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer831333290" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer359344316789515737">Whether you write for fun, casual interest, or because you&apos;re seriously pursuing a career in the field, you will inevitably come across writers who inspire you. Sometimes they inspire you because they&apos;re so terrible you think surely you can do better &amp; sometimes they inspire you because they&apos;re so good they get your creative blood flowing in a frenzied rush &amp; you can&apos;t wait to pick up a pencil &amp; get to it. Jorge Luis Borges doesn&apos;t fall in either of these categories, he falls into the category i</span>
  <span id="freeText359344316789515737" style="display:none">Whether you write for fun, casual interest, or because you're seriously pursuing a career in the field, you will inevitably come across writers who inspire you. Sometimes they inspire you because they're so terrible you think surely you can do better &amp; sometimes they inspire you because they're so good they get your creative blood flowing in a frenzied rush &amp; you can't wait to pick up a pencil &amp; get to it. Jorge Luis Borges doesn't fall in either of these categories, he falls into the category inhabited by few other writers. After you read these writers you will see no point in writing anything for whatever your reasons for writing may be, because, to put it quite simply, there is no point. They have done it all. They have put letters into words &amp; words into phrases &amp; these captivate you &amp; amaze you in a way that's almost unreal. What they do with words is not what the rest of us do with words. Their words are powerful, they're like weapons against the mundane, the pointless, the things we thought dead &amp; in turn we come alive from having read them &amp; we want to re-read them just to be in that beautiful dome they create. This book had me at the opening &amp; left me lost at the close, if only because I want to read it again. What this man did with his words, his creativity, his mind, is every kind of beautiful there is. </span>
  <a data-text-id="359344316789515737" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


