<div id="review_57609240" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/57609240" />
    <a title="Manday" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1794335-manday"><img alt="Manday" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1239419459p2/1794335.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/57609240?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manday" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manday" href="/user/show/1794335-manday">Manday</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1794335-manday?shelf=seasonal-challenge-2009-fall">seasonal-challenge-2009-fall</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1794335-manday?shelf=2009">2009</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1794335-manday?shelf=fantasy-scifi">fantasy-scifi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1794335-manday?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer57609240" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7849516862760921412">This book is titled &quot;The Book of Sand&quot; after one of its short stories. In that short story, The Book of Sand is called such because it is a book with no beginning and no end and no pattern to its pages. I think it makes a suitable title for the collection of stories as a whole, though for slightly different reasons. When I read this book, trying to keep a grasp on the stories and their meanings and interconnectedness was like trying to hold a handful of sand - always slipping away, finding ways </span>
  <span id="freeText7849516862760921412" style="display:none">This book is titled "The Book of Sand" after one of its short stories. In that short story, The Book of Sand is called such because it is a book with no beginning and no end and no pattern to its pages. I think it makes a suitable title for the collection of stories as a whole, though for slightly different reasons. When I read this book, trying to keep a grasp on the stories and their meanings and interconnectedness was like trying to hold a handful of sand - always slipping away, finding ways to leak out through my fingers and off the edges. <br /><br />It was a good read. I did get a better grasp on things as I read more and more of the stories Borges seems to have certain themes which he returns to over and over, and once you get a grasp on these, holding on to the rest is easier. For example, "The Book of Sand" is about the horror which surrounds things that defy our reality and cause obsession - very similar to the theme of "The Blue Tiger" in which a man starts to be driven insane by blue discs that do not follow the law of mathematics. He also has a preoccupation with facing your past or future self, or facing the future.<br /><br />Anyways, it is worth the read! </span>
  <a data-text-id="7849516862760921412" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


