<div id="review_2457517830" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2457517830" />
    <a title="Kartik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31291929-kartik"><img alt="Kartik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478617541p2/31291929.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2457517830?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kartik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kartik" href="/user/show/31291929-kartik">Kartik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2457517830" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10780609773971708255">Reading Borges has been on my list for years now. Finding copies of his books though, has been anything but straightforward, which, in hindsight, feels quite apt. In any case, it was more than worth it.<br/><br/>Borges&apos; literary output in the fiction department consists of numerous short stories (mostly under 10 pages long), that manage to condense a number of themes within them. <br/><br/>The stories touch upon various themes and ideas, reflecting Borges&apos; own interests and reading. They jump from mathematics, phil</span>
  <span id="freeText10780609773971708255" style="display:none">Reading Borges has been on my list for years now. Finding copies of his books though, has been anything but straightforward, which, in hindsight, feels quite apt. In any case, it was more than worth it.<br /><br />Borges' literary output in the fiction department consists of numerous short stories (mostly under 10 pages long), that manage to condense a number of themes within them. <br /><br />The stories touch upon various themes and ideas, reflecting Borges' own interests and reading. They jump from mathematics, philosophy, the gaucho culture of the Southern Cone of South America (basically the region's equivalent of the Wild West), classics and writings in Old English, Old Norse, and Latin, and a lot more. <br /><br />Couple this with a calculated economy in phrasing and word choice, fluid narratives that take the form of detective stories, personal anecdotes, and even book reviews (with all the different possibilities open to these various forms of narration), and you have yourself a collection of absolutely spellbinding stories. The stories all have an underlying element of magical realism paired with realistic mystique, occupying the limbo between everyday wonder, and the haunting nearness of daydreams. The omnipresent allusions and only serve to reinforce this net of references and ties to obscure corners of consciousness and memory. <br /><br />Borges takes great delight in making it sound like the fictional events, people, texts, and even cultural observations in his stories are real, and it shows. It only adds to the immersive experience.<br /><br /><i>The Book Of Sand &amp; Shakespeare's Memory</i>, both written towards the end of Borges' career, both feature his distinctive, eclectic, and - dare I say it - magical brand of storytelling. They mostly feature narrative meditations on the nature of infinity, and of memory. Figures, given that the aging Borges was nearing the end of his life.<br /><br /><i>Undr, Shakespeare's Memory, Blue Tigers, The Book Of Sand</i> stand out as the most magical stories in this collection, their magic staying with you long after you've finished reading them.<br /><br /><i>Undr</i> is a tale that follows a quest for the very essence of poetry, a tale set against the backdrop of warring Germanic tribes and their customs.<br /><br /><i>Shakespeare's Memory</i> deals with the nature of memory, and how its almost all-consuming depths can become a reality of its own.<br /><br /><i>Blue Tigers</i> is a story that's simultaneously a hunting story, but ends with questions that are much more unnerving than an actual tiger.<br /><br /><i>The Book Of Sand</i>, one of the best stories of the collection, deals with the nature of infinity and infinite information, a metaphor that seems to apply to us in the digital world.<br /><br />This collection of magical, haunting stories will leave a lasting impression on you. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10780609773971708255" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

