    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1807267688" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1807267688" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42975741-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1807267688?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/42975741-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780525069928" href="/book/show/849970.The_Book_of_Sand">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1807267688" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15646920098646043556">The first story (&quot;The Other&quot;) feels like a story that Borges not only could have written in his sleep, but did; the second (&quot;Ulrike&quot;) didn&apos;t even have that much going for it, as it failed to elicit any connection from me at all. &quot;The Congress&quot; comes third, and is probably what I would consider the best story here; I hoped that the collection just got off to a slow start (like this story did, progressing from an initial banality that seems intended to lull the reader into a false sense of normalc</span>
  <span id="freeText15646920098646043556" style="display:none">The first story ("The Other") feels like a story that Borges not only could have written in his sleep, but did; the second ("Ulrike") didn't even have that much going for it, as it failed to elicit any connection from me at all. "The Congress" comes third, and is probably what I would consider the best story here; I hoped that the collection just got off to a slow start (like this story did, progressing from an initial banality that seems intended to lull the reader into a false sense of normalcy, to the extent possible in a Borges story), and my hopes seemed to be validated by the following two stories, each of which successively declines a bit in quality. "There Are More Things" very effectively ends just before what might be more traditionally rendered as the climax of the story it tells; "The Sect of the Thirty" repeats this trick with the effect dulled both because of immediately following a story using the same device, but also because Borges adds a second layer of artifice to this machination, so instead of merely being an authorial choice, he presents it as a circumstance of the story being told, reducing its power by making it seem happenstance. This intentionality on one level and lack of intentionality on another jives perfectly with one of the story's elements, but at the expense of its impact. But following that, the quality of the stories tails off again significantly, with Borges' stories again fitting the molds of those first two stories. "The Night of the Gifts," "Utopia of a Tired Man," and "Arredondo" find him back in sleepwalking mode; "The Mirror and the Mask," "Undr," and "The Bribe" left me cold. None of these produce or provoke the endless thought that is the expected result of a Borges story, or even much thought at all, really; their twists aren't substantive, recontextualizing turns of events, but are closer to simply cutesy tricks, weightless technical achievements. The collection is redeemed by its closing two stories, both in contention for the best of the bunch, "The Disk" and "The Book of Sand," two stories which present mysterious objects and humans who make themselves prisoners of them by being unable to resist their fascination, despite the inability to decipher their meanings or significances. In part because of their quality, in part because of placement, they are two of the stories most likely to remain memorable, but in all honesty, I'm not sure how long even the best of these will linger in my mind, something I've never had to say before about a Borges collection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15646920098646043556" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

